5. Ghost Roots (Fossilized Operator Cores)

English inherited many Latin roots that only appear with prefixes. They act like semantic operators.

Receive-family

Root: -ceive / -cept (from Latin capere “to take”)

Word	Meaning
receive	take in
perceive	take through senses
conceive	take into the mind
deceive	take wrongly

Root operator:

ceive = take

⸻

Mit-family

Root: -mit / -miss (Latin mittere “send”)

Word	Meaning
transmit	send across
submit	send under
emit	send out
permit	send through / allow

Operator:

mit = send

⸻

Pose-family

Root: -pose / -posit (Latin ponere “place”)

Word	Meaning
compose	place together
impose	place upon
oppose	place against
deposit	place down

Operator:

pose = place

⸻

Clude-family

Root: -clude / -clus (Latin claudere “close”)

Word	Meaning
include	close inside
exclude	close out
conclude	close together

Operator:

clude = close

⸻

Scribe-family

Root: -scribe / -script

Word	Meaning
describe	write down
prescribe	write before
manuscript	written by hand

Operator:

scribe = write

