7. Something Wild About Language Architecture

Here’s the surprising part.

Most Indo-European languages are built from about 200–300 root concepts.

These roots behave like a primitive operator library.

Examples of universal conceptual primitives:
	•	take
	•	give
	•	move
	•	see
	•	break
	•	build
	•	turn
	•	speak
	•	bind
	•	cut

Everything else is composition.

This means language functions a lot like:

semantic programming

Where words are compiled meaning functions.

⸻

8. Why Ghost Roots Matter

Ghost roots reveal something interesting about cognition:

Humans think in operations, not nouns.

Actions are primary:
	•	move
	•	take
	•	build
	•	break

Objects are secondary.

That’s why languages keep these operator cores even when speakers forget their origin.

